  "prompt": "What does it mean when your left eye twitches?",
  "response": "Eye twitching, also known as myokymia, can be caused by various factors. Common reasons for a twitching left eye (or right eye) include:\n\n1. **Stress**: High levels of stress can trigger eye twitches.\n2. **Fatigue**: Lack of sleep or excessive tiredness can cause eye muscles to twitch.\n3. **Eye strain**: Prolonged screen time or reading without breaks can lead to eye strain and twitching.\n4. **Caffeine or Alcohol**: Excessive intake of caffeine or alcohol can contribute to eye twitching.\n5. **Dry eyes**: If your eyes are dry, they may start to twitch as a response.\n6. **Nutritional imbalances**: Lack of certain nutrients like magnesium can sometimes cause muscle spasms, including eye twitches.\n7. **Allergies**: Allergic reactions can lead to eye irritation and twitching.\n\nIn most cases, eye twitching is harmless and resolves on its own. However, if the twitching persists for an extended period, is accompanied by other symptoms, or affects other parts of the face, it may be advisable to consult a healthcare professional to rule out more serious conditions.\n\nIt's important to manage stress, get adequate sleep, limit screen time, and maintain a balanced diet to prevent eye twitching.",
